1. **Initialization**:  
One way to avoid a `NullPointerException` is to ensure that the variable is initialized with a non-null value before it is used. For example:  
```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String name = "John"; // Initialize name to a non-null value
        System.out.println(name.length());
    }
}
```
In this example, the `name` variable is assigned the value `"John"`, which is a non-null string. As a result, calling the `length()` method on `name` will not cause any issues.

2. **Null check**:  
Another approach is to check whether the variable is null before attempting to use it. This can be done using an `if` statement, as shown below:  
```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String name = null;
        if (name != null) {
            System.out.println(name.length());
        } else {
            System.out.println("Name is null");
        }
    }
}
```
